<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06262235 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06262235 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  PRODUCT; CONSUMER  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  IF YOU want to shop green, here are some guidelines:;   (check) Chooseproducts with the least packaging. More than 30 percent of what we buy ispackaging -- and products with less packaging usually cost less.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Food  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  READ PACKAGING CLAIMS, AND REMEMBER, LESS IS BEST  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  See also related article on page 1D of this section.  </MEMO><TEXT>     (check) Look for products that have not been treated with and don't containtoxic chemicals. Unbleached coffee filters, for instance, and Borax or bakingsoda for laundry whiteners.;   (check) Look for specifics about &quot;recycled&quot;products. How much recycled material does it contain? It may vary from 10percent to 100 percent.;   (check) Don't be taken in by &quot;recyclable&quot; claims onproducts you can't recycle yourself. Know what is recyclable in your area.;  (check) Dismiss claims of degradability. Virtually nothing degrades quickly ina sealed landfill. And some things that do degrade quickly aren't necessarilysafe for the environment. Detergents, for instance, emit toxic chemicals asthey break down.;   (check) Ignore &quot;ozone-friendly&quot; labels -- especially thoseboasting that they contain no CFCs or chlorofluorocarbons. The federalgovernment banned CFCs in 1978. Aerosols still contain hydrocarbons thatcontribute to smog. Look instead for spray bottles that don't require chemicalpropellants.; IFYOU'RE INTERESTED; &quot;The Green Consumer Supermarket Guide&quot;(Penguin, $6.95) is an aisle-by-aisle shopping guide that lists brand names ofearth-friendly products and companies.;   Green Consumer Letter ($27 peryear), a monthly newsletter, covers new products, evaluates companies' claimsand offers money-saving tips. For a free issue, send a self-addressed,legal-size envelope stamped with 52 cents postage to Green Consumer Letter,Dept. CT, 1526 Connecticut Ave. N.W., Washington, D.C. 20036.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  SUE ELLYN SCALETTA, Knight-Ridder News Service  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910918  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  September  </MONTH><PG.COL>  4D  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  268  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday, September 18, 199100262235,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>